				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Banned . . . for how long, forever?<a name="69767"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 15 04 4:56 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">It really is too vague to be any use except to GMs who feel like using that clause against people. </span></blockquote>
<br />
I'm confused.  Who <b><i>else</i></b>, other than the GMs, are going to &quot;use that clause against people&quot;?  What possible use could a player like you or me have for a EULA?
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Would using my Logitech Mouseware software to program the middle button to a specific function be in violation? It would seem so... </span></blockquote>
<br />
&quot;It would seem so&quot;?  Of course it would.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Does mapping hotkeys to buttons on my Nostromo count? It requires software to do that, and it does Affect Gameplay... </span></blockquote>
<br />
Absolutely.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">How about using something like Teamspeak, so you have voice communication with other people you group with? This uses software, and it most certainly Affects Gameplay. </span></blockquote>
<br />
Of course.  And it's illegal.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">AFK instrument training does not require software, nor does afk autocircle swimming for skill ups. It can be fairly annoying to have someone practicing Brass in the Bazaar, but not actionable under the clause prohibiting 3rd Party Software. </span></blockquote>
<br />
Of course not.  You could consider it a violation of the Play Nice rules, and if enough people complain, it could get some GM intervention, but as you correctly state, there's nothing there that would get a player banned...unless it was a recurring problem...which would be actionable under other rules.
<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I'd imagine that they can't find a legal way to enforce a ban on what they really *want* to ban, which is Unattended Operation. How do they prove you are not there? </span></blockquote>
<br />
Well, that takes the argument to a completely different arena.  Nobody's been asking how they prove you're there or not.  People have been asking &quot;is this a violation of the EULA or not?&quot;  A subtle difference, but definitely a difference.
<br />

<br />
Yes.  All of the things you listed above are violations, because they involve the use of external software to affect in-game play.  I realize you were being sarcastic, listing things that everybody would <b><i>obviously</i></b> agree aren't violations, because they're so trivial.  But, the truth is, under strict interpretation of the EULA...yes...they're all violations.
<br />

<br />
But, again, that's not the point.  The point is, are they <b><i>enough</i></b> of a violation...so obviously a violation that they pretty much <b><i>require</i></b> an action?  Well, no...they're not.  Which is why you thought it was so funny to think they could <b><i>possibly</i></b> be considered violations...and which is why people don't get banned for using them.  They don't effect the game enough for it to be obvious to a 3rd-party observer that a violation is occurring.  Yes, they're all violations, but since nobody but the person breaking the rule could know, obviously you won't get banned for it (nor should you, for any of the minor infractions you listed here to try and make your point).
<br />

<br />
People argue the EULA as if it's a club that Sony uses against players all the time...but I think I know of about 3-4 people in my 4+ years of experience who've been banned for EULA violations...and all of them pretty obvious violations.  Sony shows a lot more tolerance for questionable violations than they're given credit for, in my opinion.  But, if you're doing something that is <b><i>obviously</i></b> a violation to anybody looking on (like sitting in one spot, non-communicative, casting the same spell over and over in excess of 8 hours), then the person doing it shouldn't be surprised when the GMs say or do something about it.  </span></td>
			</tr><tr>
