				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">So in teacher-speak, he got caught cheating on a test and is now upset with the teacher for giving him no credit for the test?</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Not the point.  We don't think he cheated.
<br />

<br />
It is our opinion that the EULA was vague on Nostromo's.  <i>And</i> that using a Nostromo does not change game play enough to constitute cheating.  
<br />

<br />
Many in this thread have an opposite opinion.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">are we suppose to feel sad for this guy?</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Nope, not looking for that.  Just gathering opinions of what other people think.  My friend may leave, I may too, but that will be because I lost a friend in the game.  Not because he got banned.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote"> i like his horrible overgeneralizations...like every one i know uses one HA </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Not overgeneralization.  We are a tight group.  We adventure almost exclusively within our group.  Small family guild.  While ALL is not accurate,  many of us do use one.
<br />

<br />
Look.  I play a Ranger,  too.  So I got a quandry here with a common scenario:  when I'm playing in the planes with pet classes, there isn't much I can do without a Cleric/Slower other than pluck with arrows.  To make things easier and take the boredom from hittin 9 9 9 9 9, I roll the wheel up.
<br />

<br />
Rolling that wheel up to auto-archery is fixing a deficiency in the game, for example.  Not cheating, IMO.  Why do I hit with a sword without hitting a key,  but not an arrow?
<br />

<br />
And now,  auto-archery is something that will now be added to the game.  Again,  before it was cheating,  now a part of the game.  Why is that?  I was wrong and cheated before, and now I'll be ok moral and a stand-up citizen of Norrath.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
If we are to look at the rules and judge them effectively, we must look at their intent.  What negative effect are they supposed to stop?
<br />

<br />
If we do not judge them on their intent and only judge by the letter of the law, they become rules for the sake of rules.  They become sclerotic and ineffectual.
<br />

<br />

